<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="104" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="37.[227,372,1185,1211]" box="[227,372,1185,1211]" pageId="37" pageNumber="104">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,372,1185,1211]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="37" pageNumber="104" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,372,1185,1211]" pageId="37" pageNumber="104">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[227,1437,1232,1435]" pageId="37" pageNumber="104">
Specimen MB.C.30487 is a body chamber fragment that belonged to a conch approximately 
<quantity box="[1351,1437,1232,1259]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="37" pageNumber="104" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
diameter (
<figureCitation box="[346,435,1267,1294]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="37.[227,270,1999,2025]" captionTargetBox="[596,1058,1530,1949]" captionTargetId="figure-277@37.[590,1072,1527,1956]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Fig. 30. Lispoceras sp. 1, specimen MB.C.30487 from Oued Temertasset (Korn et al. 2002 Coll.); lateral view and whorl profile. Scale bar units =1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902652" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902652/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="104">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). It has an almost circular whorl profile with a slightly clearer umbilical margin. The last whorl only slightly encompassed the previous one, recognisable by the very small dorsal whorl zone. The shell surface, although marred by desert grinding, is clearly recognisable. The ornament consists of fine growth lines running in a slightly posterior direction across the umbilical wall and flanks, then forming a deep ventral sinus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
